  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats context as constructed runtime truth, not as an accidental by-product of ingestion"]
    L2["It is also not something decisioning should just figure out later"]
    L3["Admitted traffic alone is not enough"]
    L4["The system must deliberately bind flow-level, arrival-level, and entity-level context into joined surface"]
    L5["It must do so honestly enough that downstream components are not fooled by partial or stale context"]
    L6["That is why the RTDL docs emphasize false-ready, missing-context drift, role-reference correctness, and fanout bounds at this boundary"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The path is seated across admitted traffic and context topics on the runtime bus"]
    S2["The RTDL namespace and worker surfaces consume those topics"]
    S3["The context-store and flow-binding surface sits inside the RTDL namespace"]
    S4["The traffic topic is consumed by the context-store and flow-binding surface"]
    S5["Arrival-events, arrival-entities, and flow-anchor context topics are consumed by that same surface"]
    S6["Joined context is projected onward to the entity and graph and feature components"]
    S7["This is concretely realized as event-bus intake plus RTDL worker surface plus downstream context handoff"]
    S8["Managed stream-processing surfaces remain retained in the broader repo authority rather than the primary reader-facing active output path in this notebook's copied baseline wired view"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform deliberately chose thin-traffic, in-platform-join posture"]
    Y2["It rejected putting too much context into the traffic payload"]
    Y3["It rejected using batch-only or future-implying fields like session_end_utc or arrival_count"]
    Y4["It rejected collapsing context truth into downstream feature or decision logic"]
    Y5["Instead, the interface contract pins time-safe context surfaces and the binding join map"]
    Y6["The RTDL framing pins joined-context creation as its own truth boundary with its own false-ready discipline"]
    Y7["The current shape exists because the platform is trying to keep traffic thin, context explicit, and timing semantics honest"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The engine interface shapes the semantic side"]
    X2["Only behavioural streams are traffic"]
    X3["Joins occur inside the platform"]
    X4["Only time-safe context surfaces may be used in RTDL"]
    X5["Batch-only truth products and future-implying fields are forbidden for live decisions"]
    X6["The run-process shapes the closure side by giving RTDL inlet and projection closure explicit phase boundary in RTDL catch-up closure"]
    X7["The RTDL plan shapes the observability side by treating false-ready, join completeness, unmatched joins, and fanout bounds as key proof surfaces for this boundary"]
    X8["So this path is strongly shaped by time-safety law, closure law, and boundary-specific observability law"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately chooses more structure in exchange for cleaner runtime truth"]
    T2["It would be easier to flatten more context into the event or let downstream components infer missing context opportunistically"]
    T3["The current design rejects that because it would blur the truth boundary and make later errors hard to interpret"]
    T4["The cost is more explicit join discipline, more state and projection dependence, and stricter readiness semantics"]
    T5["It also forbids apparently convenient inputs like s1_session_index_6B in live runtime because those fields imply future knowledge and would corrupt temporal correctness"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still ingest traffic, maintain entity projection, and draw later boxes like online feature readiness, decision guardrail, and decision formation"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to how admitted event becomes the specific runtime context downstream components actually consume"]
    N3["It also loses a clean answer to whether the flow, arrival, and entity bindings are complete"]
    N4["It becomes unclear whether ready means full context or only partial context"]
    N5["It becomes unclear whether missing context is a context problem or a decision problem"]
    N6["Without this path, the rest of RTDL would start looking like a decision system built on unowned or implicit context assumptions"]
    N7["That would weaken A immediately"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Joined, time-safe runtime context surface exists"]
    O2["The admitted event is bound into the right arrival, flow, and entity context"]
    O3["Readiness posture is honest for downstream RTDL consumers"]
    O4["Owned outcome: joined runtime context and readiness truth for downstream RTDL use"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for creating joined runtime context surface before feature or decision work begins"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>context is built from thin traffic plus explicit time-safe join surfaces using a pinned join map"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the path is concretely seated in the runtime bus topics, the RTDL namespace and context-store surface, the downstream handoff into the entity and graph and feature surfaces, and the RTDL catch-up phase boundary"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>the path is constrained by the live-runtime-allowed output set, no-future rules, and join-key discipline"]
    A5["Quantified closure claim:<br/>the current runtime context boundary is built from a bounded four-surface live-runtime set rather than an unbounded or hand-wavy source world"]
    A6["A-level meaning:<br/>the platform turns thin admitted traffic into honest, time-safe runtime context rather than leaving downstream RTDL to guess what context exists"]
  end

